content.problemStatement:
**Without ApplicationContext (Old Way)**
```java
BookService bookService = new BookService();
EmailNotificationService emailService = new EmailNotificationService();
```

**Problems:**
- You manage everything manually
- Tight coupling
- Hard to change implementations

---

**With ApplicationContext (Spring Way)**
```java
@Service
public class BookService {

    @Autowired
    private EmailNotificationService emailService;
}
```
- No new
- Spring injects dependencies
- ApplicationContext handles everything

---

**ApplicationContext in Spring Boot** 
```java
@SpringBootApplication
public class LibraryApplication {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SpringApplication.run(LibraryApplication.class, args);
    }
}
```
In Spring Boot, **you do NOT create ApplicationContext manually**.

```java
SpringApplication.run(LibraryApplication.class, args);
```
**This line:**
- **Creates the `ApplicationContext`**
- Scans all beans
- Starts the application

---

**So in Spring Boot:** \
You start the app using `run()` **→** \
Spring creates the `ApplicationContext` **→** \
`ApplicationContext` creates and manages all beans 

**This is why `ApplicationContext` is the heart of Spring Boot**.

